                                                       "clustering"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The assessment of an AI system's clustering."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00146
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00146> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03642> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/0377-0427(87)90125-7> ;
                                         rdfs:label "coeficiente de silueta"@es ,
                                                    "silhouette coefficient"@en ,
                                                    "silhouette coefficient"@zh ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silhouette_(clustering)> ,
                                                      <https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Silhouette_(clustering)> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "silhouette"@en ,
                                                       "valor de la silueta"@es ;
                                         skos:definition "The silhouette value is a measure of how similar an object is to its own cluster (cohesion) compared to other clusters (separation). The silhouette value ranges from −1 to +1, where a high value indicates that the object is well matched to its own cluster and poorly matched to neighboring clusters."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00147
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00147> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03642> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1080/03610927408827101> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Calinski-Harabasz 指数"@zh ,
                                                    "variance ratio criterion"@en ,
                                                    "índice de Calinski-Harabasz"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CHI"@en ,
                                                       "Calinski-Harabasz index"@en ,
                                                       "VRC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Calinski–Harabasz index (CHI), also known as the Variance Ratio Criterion (VRC), is an internal metric for evaluating clustering algorithms, where the assessment of the clustering quality is based solely on the dataset and the clustering results, and not on external, ground-truth labels."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00148
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00148> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.11997> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.54364/AAIML.2023.1161> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "P4 = 4 / (1/precision + 1/recall + 1/specificity + 1/NPV)"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "P4 metric"@en ,
                                                    "P4 指标"@zh ,
                                                    "métrica P4"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P4-metric> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FS"@en ,
                                                       "P4"@en ,
                                                       "P4-metric"@en ,
                                                       "symmetric F"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The P4 metric, also known as FS or Symmetric F, enables performance evaluation of a binary classifier: it is calculated from precision, recall, specificity, and negative predictive value."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00149
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00149> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03642> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1080/01969727308546046> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Dunn index"@en ,
                                                    "Dunn 指数"@zh ,
                                                    "índice de Dunn"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunn_index> ;
                                         skos:definition "The Dunn index, a metric for evaluating clustering algorithms, is part of a group of validity indices including the Davies–Bouldin index or Silhouette index, in that it is an internal evaluation scheme, where the result is based on the clustered data itself."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00150
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00150> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03642> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "The Hopkins statistic (introduced by Brian Hopkins and John Gordon Skellam) is a way of measuring the cluster tendency of a data set. It belongs to the family of sparse sampling tests. It acts as a statistical hypothesis test where the null hypothesis is that the data is generated by a Poisson point process and are thus uniformly randomly distributed. If individuals are aggregated, then its value approaches 1, and if they are randomly distributed along the value tends to 0.5. [Wikipedia]"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "Hopkins statistic"@en ,
                                                    "Hopkins statistic"@zh ,
                                                    "estadístico de Hopkins"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "霍普金斯统计量"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "The Hopkins statistic is a way of measuring the cluster tendency of a data set."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0.5 ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00151
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00151> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03642> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1137/1.9781611973440.96> ;
                                         rdfs:label "density-based clustering validation"@en ,
                                                    "density-based clustering validation"@zh ,
                                                    "validación de agrupación basada en densidad"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Density-based_clustering_validation> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "DBCV"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Density-Based Clustering Validation (DBCV) is a metric designed to assess the quality of clustering solutions, particularly for density-based clustering algorithms like DBSCAN, Mean shift, and OPTICS. This metric is particularly suited for identifying concave and nested clusters, where traditional metrics such as the Silhouette coefficient, Davies–Bouldin index, or Calinski–Harabasz index often struggle to provide meaningful evaluations."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00152
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00152> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.2214/AJR.25.34340> ;
                                         rdfs:label "number needed to benefit"@en ,
                                                    "number needed to benefit"@zh ,
                                                    "número de casos necesarios para obtener un beneficio"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NNB"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The number needed to benefit (NNB) is defined as the reciprocal of the absolute enhanced detection rate (i.e., total number of cases needed to review to achieve one AI true-positive that the radiologist alone would miss). The number of positive cases needed to benefit is defined as the reciprocal of the relative enhanced detection rate (i.e., number of radiologist true-positives needed to achieve one AI true-positive that the radiologist alone would miss).These two metrics are analogous to the number needed to treat metric used in clinical decision making."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00153
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00153> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.2214/AJR.25.34340> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "GPR serves as a measure of a model’s net benefit by comparing the gain from additional reference-standard positive cases detected with AI assistance to the so-called “pain” from AI false-positives."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "gain-to-pain ratio"@en ,
                                                    "gain-to-pain ratio"@zh ,
                                                    "relación beneficio-dolor"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "GPR"@en ,
                                                       "gain to pain ratio"@en ,
                                                       "gain-to-pain"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The gain-to-pain ratio (GPR) is defined as the ratio between the number of enhanced detection cases and number of AI false-positive cases."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00154
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00154> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.2214/AJR.25.34340> ;
                                         rdfs:label "number of positive cases needed to benefit"@en ,
                                                    "number of positive cases needed to benefit"@zh ,
                                                    "número de casos positivos necesarios para obtener un beneficio"@es ;
                                         skos:definition "The number of positive cases needed to benefit is defined as the reciprocal of the relative enhanced detection rate (i.e., number of radiologist true-positives needed to achieve one AI true-positive that the radiologist alone would miss)."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00156
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00156> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03651> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         rdfs:label "nivel de dificultad de lectura"@es ,
                                                    "reading difficulty level"@en ,
                                                    "reading difficulty level"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "grade reading level"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The grade reading level (or reading difficulty level) is calculated by the average number of sentences (y-axis) and syllables (x-axis) per hundred words."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00160
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00160> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04043> ;
                                         rdfs:label "ranking performance"@en ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranking_(information_retrieval)> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "ranking"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Ranking is one of the fundamental problems in information retrieval (IR). Given a query q and a collection D of documents that match the query, the problem is to rank, that is, sort, the documents in D according to some criterion so that the \"best\" results appear early in the result list displayed to the user."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00161
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00161> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03650> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://proceedings.mlr.press/v30/Wang13.html> ;
                                         rdfs:label "discounted cumulative gain"@en ,
                                                    "ganancia acumulada descontada"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discounted_cumulative_gain> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "DCG"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Discounted cumulative gain (DCG) is a measure of ranking quality in information retrieval."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00162
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00162> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03650> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1145/582415.582418> ,
                                                   <https://proceedings.mlr.press/v30/Wang13.html> ;
                                         rdfs:label "cumulative gain"@en ,
                                                    "ganancia acumulada"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discounted_cumulative_gain> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CG"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Cumulative Gain is the sum of the graded relevance values of all results in a search result list. CG does not take into account the rank (position) of a result in the result list."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00163
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00163> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03650> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://proceedings.mlr.press/v30/Wang13.html> ;
                                         rdfs:label "ganancia acumulada descontada normalizada"@es ,
                                                    "normalized discounted cumulative gain"@en ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discounted_cumulative_gain> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NDCG"@en ,
                                                       "nDCG"@en ,
                                                       "normalised DCG"@en ,
                                                       "normalised discounted cumulative gain"@en ,
                                                       "normalized DCG"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Normalized discounted cumulative gain (NDCG) measures the performance of a recommendation system based on the graded relevance of the recommended entities. It varies from 0.0 to 1.0, with 1.0 representing the ideal ranking of the entities. This metric is commonly used in information retrieval and to evaluate the performance of web search engines."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00164
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00164> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00163> ;
                                         rdfs:label "NDGC@k"@en ,
                                                    "ganancia acumulada descontada normalizada en k entradas"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "normalized discounted cumulative gain @ k entries"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """Normalized discounted cumulative gain (NDCG) measures the performance of a recommendation system based on the graded relevance of the recommended entities. It varies from 0.0 to 1.0, with 1.0 representing the ideal ranking of the entities. This metric is commonly used in information retrieval and to evaluate the performance of web search engines. 

                                         Parameters:
                                         k = The maximum number of entities that can be recommended"""@en .


