###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03217
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03217> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03307> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12859-015-0564-6> ;
                                         rdfs:label "lenient accuracy"@en ,
                                                    "precisión flexible"@es ,
                                                    "宽松的准确性"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "LACC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Lenient accuracy is a relaxed evaluation metric that considers a response correct if any of the system’s returned answers matches one of the acceptable gold-standard answers. Unlike strict accuracy, it allows for synonyms, equivalent expressions, or alternative correct forms, making it more tolerant in domains where multiple valid answer variants exist. It is frequently used in factoid question answering to avoid penalizing systems for producing correct but differently worded outputs."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03218
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03218> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03580> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1080/02664763.2016.1174195> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1177/0962280214537390> ;
                                         rdfs:label "coeficiente de variación de segundo orden"@es ,
                                                    "second-order coefficient of variation"@en ,
                                                    "二阶变异系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CV2"@en ,
                                                       "CV_2"@en ,
                                                       "V2"@en ,
                                                       "V_2"@en ,
                                                       "normalized coefficient of variation"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The second-order coefficient of variation is an alternative formulation that expresses relative variability as the ratio of the standard deviation to the square root of the second raw moment. Unlike the classical coefficient of variation, it is always defined for real-valued data, bounded between 0 and 1, and less sensitive to extreme values. Its bounded range and geometric interpretation as a ratio of distances make it a more robust and interpretable measure of dispersion."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03219
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03219> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03652> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.4103/crst.crst_283_23> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error estándar relativo"@es ,
                                                    "relative standard error"@en ,
                                                    "相对标准误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "RSE"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The relative standard error is a percentage-based measure of the reliability of an estimate, defined as the standard error divided by the estimate itself and multiplied by 100. It expresses the precision of the estimate relative to its magnitude, with smaller values indicating greater reliability. Estimates with large RSE values are often considered too unstable for reporting and may be flagged, suppressed, or presented with cautionary notes."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03220
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03220> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.acra.2014.07.004> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1080/10543400701329489> ;
                                         rdfs:label "individual equivalence index"@en ,
                                                    "índice de equivalencia individual"@es ,
                                                    "个体等效指数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "IEC"@en ,
                                                       "IEI"@en ,
                                                       "individual equivalence coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "interchangeability metric"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The individual equivalence index is a statistical measure used to determine whether a new diagnostic method can be considered interchangeable with a reference method. It is defined as the probability that the new test and the reference test provide the same result, relative to the probability that two independent replicates of the reference agree with each other. Values close to one indicate that the new test agrees with the reference to the same degree as the reference agrees with itself, making the index a tool for formally assessing interchangeability in diagnostic imaging and related settings."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03221
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03221> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04053> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/TIT.2005.844059> ;
                                         rdfs:label "distancia de compresión normalizada"@es ,
                                                    "normalized compression distance"@en ,
                                                    "归一化压缩距离"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NCD"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Normalized compression distance is a practical approximation of normalized information distance that replaces Kolmogorov complexity with the length of compressed data produced by a real-world compression algorithm. It measures the relative similarity of two objects by comparing the compression of each individually with the compression of their concatenation, yielding values close to zero for highly similar objects and close to one for dissimilar ones. While dependent on the choice of compressor and only approximately metric, it provides a widely usable, domain-independent method for quantifying similarity across diverse data types."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03222
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03222> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03314> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0006-341X.2000.00337.x> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0006-341X.2005.030814.x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "time-dependent area under the receiver operating characteristic curve"@en ,
                                                    "área bajo la curva ROC dependiente del tiempo"@es ,
                                                    "时间依赖性受试者工作特征曲线下面积"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AUC at time (t)"@en ,
                                                       "AUC(t)"@en ,
                                                       "area under the receiver operating curve at time (t)"@en ,
                                                       "time-dependent AUC"@en ,
                                                       "time-specific AUC"@en ,
                                                       "time-specific area under the receiver operating characteristic curve"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The time-dependent area under the receiver operating characteristic curve is a measure of a prognostic marker’s or model’s ability to discriminate between individuals who will experience an event by a specified time and those who will remain event-free. It generalizes the classical area under the curve to survival data by defining cases and controls dynamically over time and computing the probability that a subject with an event has a higher predicted risk than one without an event at time t. This metric provides a time-specific summary of discriminatory accuracy in the presence of censoring and evolving event status."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03223
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03223> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03655> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.3348/kjr.2021.0223> ;
                                         rdfs:label "integrated time-dependent area under the ROC curve"@en ,
                                                    "área bajo la curva ROC integrada dependiente del tiempo"@es ,
                                                    "集成时间依赖性ROC曲线下面积"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "iAUC"@en ,
                                                       "integrated time-dependent AUC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """An integrated AUC (iAUC) is a mathematical integration of multiple time-dependent AUC values across the follow-up period, and it can be expressed as follows: iAUC= ∫AUC(t)·w(t)dt, where t = time and w = weight. Heagerty and Zheng suggested that w(t) should be proportional to the marginal density of survival time multiplied by the survival function, which makes the iAUC equivalent to ‘concordance,’ which is the probability that the order of deaths in randomly chosen two patients agrees with the order predicted by the model. In other words, iAUC is a weighted sum or a global average of time-dependent AUC values from time-dependent ROC analyses across the follow-up duration. 
                                         - from Park SY, et al. KJR 2021."""@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03224
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03224> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00021> ;
                                         rdfs:label "autonomous diagnosis"@en ,
                                                    "diagnóstico autónomo"@es ,
                                                    "自主诊断"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CADa"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Diagnosis performed by computer without human interaction."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03225
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03225> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03643> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/IRI62200.2024.00065> ,
                                                   "D. Pessach and E. Shmueli, “Algorithmic fairness,” in Machine Learning for Data Science Handbook, pp. 867–886, Springer International Publishing, 2023."@en ;
                                         rdfs:comment "Group fairness, also known as statistical or demographic fairness, requires that predictive outcomes are independent of specific sensitive attributes such as race, gender, or age."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "equidad grupal"@es ,
                                                    "group fairness"@en ,
                                                    "群体公平性"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "demographic fairness"@en ,
                                                       "statistical fairness"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """Assuming ˆ Y is the predicted outcome and D is the sensitive attribute with a given value d, then group fairness can be expressed as: 
                                         P( ˆ Y = 1|D = d) = P( ˆ Y = 1|D <> d)"""@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03226
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03226> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03643> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/IRI62200.2024.00065> ;
                                         rdfs:label "equidad individual"@es ,
                                                    "individual fairness"@en ,
                                                    "个体公平性"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Individual fairness mandates that similar individuals should receive similar predictions. It can be mathematically formalized using a distance metric d(·), which measures the similarity between individuals: d( ˆ Yi, ˆ Yj) ≤ D(xi, xj) ∀i, j"@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03227
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03227> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03643> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/IRI62200.2024.00065> ;
                                         rdfs:label "equality of opportunity"@en ,
                                                    "igualdad de oportunidades"@es ,
                                                    "机会平等"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition """Equality of opportunity, an extension of group fairness, states that groups should have equal true positive rates. This metric is defined as:
                                         P( ˆ Y = 1|D = d, Y = 1) = P( ˆ Y = 1|D <> d, Y = 1)"""@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03228
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03228> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03643> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/IRI62200.2024.00065> ;
                                         rdfs:label "demographic parity"@en ,
                                                    "paridad demográfica"@es ,
                                                    "人口统计学平等"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "statistical parity"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """Demographic parity, also known as statistical parity, requires the decision outcomes to be independent of the sensitive attributes. It aims for the probability of a positive prediction to be the same across different groups defined by the sensitive attribute. It is defined as:
                                         P( ˆ Y = 1|D = d) = P( ˆ Y = 1|D <> d)"""@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03229
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03229> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03643> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/IRI62200.2024.00065> ;
                                         rdfs:label "equalized odds"@en ,
                                                    "probabilidades igualadas"@es ,
                                                    "均衡几率"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition """Equalized odds require that the model’s true positive rate and false positive rate be the same across groups, defined as: 
                                         P( ˆ Y = 1|D = d, Y = y) = P( ˆ Y = 1|D <> d, Y = y) for all y in {0, 1}"""@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03760> ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00631> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03616>
                                                         ] ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-024-56706-x> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "métrica escalar del rendimiento del modelo"@es ,
                                                    "scalar metric"@en ,
                                                    "模型性能的标量指标"@zh ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso "https://www.midrc.org/performance-metrics-decision-tree"@en ;
                                         skos:altLabel "scalar metric of model performance"@en ,
                                                       "scalar model performance data"@en ,
                                                       "scalar model performance metric"@en ,
                                                       "scalar performance metric"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Model performance information presented as a single numerical (scalar) value."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03307
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03307> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "accuracy"@en ,
                                                    "exactitud"@es ,
                                                    "准确性"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition """Accuracy quantifies the proportion of correct predictions made by a model across all classes. It is calculated as the number of true positives and true negatives divided by the total number of predictions. Accuracy is sensitive to class imbalance and may not reflect performance adequately in imbalanced datasets.

                                         Accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)"""@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000415" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03308
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03308> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03640> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03307> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "balanced accuracy"@en ,
                                                    "exactitud balanceada"@es ,
                                                    "平衡准确率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "BA"@en ,
                                                       "BCR"@en ,
                                                       "balanced classification rate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """Balanced accuracy measures the average proportion of correct predictions across all classes, accounting for class imbalance. In binary classification, it is defined as the mean of sensitivity (true positive rate) and specificity (true negative rate). In multi-class settings, it is calculated as the average of class-wise sensitivities, giving equal weight to each class regardless of prevalence. Balanced accuracy can be considered as the macro-averaged accuracy.

                                         BA = (TPR + TNR) / 2"""@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03309
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03309> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03658> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1001/jama.295.20.2374> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "costo esperado"@es ,
                                                    "expected cost"@en ,
                                                    "预期成本"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "EC"@en ,
                                                       "expected loss"@en ,
                                                       "expected prediction error"@en ,
                                                       "normalized cost"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Expected cost quantifies the average penalty associated with prediction errors, incorporating predefined cost values for false positives and false negatives. It generalizes accuracy by weighting error types according to their impact. This metric supports applications where decision costs vary among outcomes."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03311
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03311> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03510> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1177/001316446002000104> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Kappa de Cohen ponderado"@es ,
                                                    "weighted Cohen's kappa"@en ,
                                                    "加权科恩κ系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "WCK"@en ,
                                                       "weighted kappa"@en ,
                                                       "加权科恩卡帕系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Weighted Cohen’s kappa extends Cohen’s kappa by incorporating a weighting scheme that reflects the severity or cost of different types of misclassification. It is particularly suited for ordinal or multi-class problems, where misclassifications between distant classes can be penalized more heavily than near-misses. Like Cohen’s Kappa, its value ranges from -1 to 1, with higher scores indicating better agreement beyond chance."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03314
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03314> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1148/radiology.143.1.7063747> ;
                                         rdfs:label "area under the receiver operating characteristic curve"@en ,
                                                    "área bajo la curva característica operativa del receptor"@es ,
                                                    "接收者操作特征曲线下的面积"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AUC"@en ,
                                                       "AUC score"@en ,
                                                       "AUC-ROC"@en ,
                                                       "AUROC"@en ,
                                                       "AUROC score"@en ,
                                                       "ROC-AUC"@en ,
                                                       "area under TPR-FPR curve"@en ,
                                                       "area under the ROC curve"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The area under the receiver operating characteristic curve measures how well a model distinguishes between positive and negative classes across all possible thresholds. It represents the probability that a randomly chosen positive instance will receive a higher predicted score than a randomly chosen negative instance. This metric provides a threshold-independent assessment of a model’s discriminative ability."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000608> ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03319
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03319> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03320> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.3115/1072064.1072067> ;
                                         rdfs:label "F1 score"@en ,
                                                    "F1 分数"@zh ,
                                                    "puntaje F1"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "F1"@en ,
                                                       "F1-score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "F1 score is a specific case of the F(beta) score with β = 1, giving equal weight to precision and sensitivity. It is commonly used when both metrics are considered equally important for model evaluation. This score is widely adopted in tasks requiring balanced performance between completeness and correctness of predictions."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000628" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03320
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03320> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.3115/1072064.1072067> ;
                                         rdfs:label "F(beta) score"@en ,
                                                    "F(β) 分数"@zh ,
                                                    "puntaje F(beta)"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "F beta"@en ,
                                                       "F(β)"@en ,
                                                       "F(β) score"@en ,
                                                       "F-beta"@en ,
                                                       "F-beta score"@en ,
                                                       "F-β"@en ,
                                                       "F_β"@en ,
                                                       "Fβ"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "F(beta) score calculates the weighted harmonic mean of precision and sensitivity, where the parameter β controls the relative weight given to sensitivity. It provides a single measure that balances the trade-off between detecting positive cases and avoiding false positives. Larger β values place more emphasis on sensitivity, while smaller values emphasize precision."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000663" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03321
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03321> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.media.2010.05.005> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "free-response receiver operating characteristic score"@en ,
                                                    "puntuación de la curva ROC de respuesta libre"@es ,
                                                    "自由响应受试者工作特征分数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FROC score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The free-response receiver operating characteristic score is a performance measure that summarizes the trade-off between sensitivity and the average number of false positives per image in object-level detection tasks. It is typically derived from the free-response receiver operating characteristic curve, which plots sensitivity across a range of false positive rates per image, and can be computed either as the area under this curve or as the average sensitivity at predetermined false positive thresholds. This score accounts for both the accuracy of identifying true findings and the burden of false alarms."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03322
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03322> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-024-56706-x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "false positive rate"@en ,
                                                    "tasa de falsos positivos"@es ,
                                                    "假阳性率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FPR"@en ,
                                                       "alpha"@en ,
                                                       "error tipo 1"@es ,
                                                       "fall-out"@en ,
                                                       "fall-out rate"@en ,
                                                       "fallout"@en ,
                                                       "fallout rate"@en ,
                                                       "significance level"@en ,
                                                       "type 1 error rate"@en ,
                                                       "type I error rate"@en ,
                                                       "α"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The false positive rate is the proportion of actual negative cases that are incorrectly classified as positive by a diagnostic test or predictive model. It is calculated as the number of false positives divided by the sum of false positives and true negatives, making it the complement of specificity. FPR indicates how often non-existent conditions are mistakenly detected and serves as the x-axis dimension in receiver operating characteristic (ROC) analysis."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000053" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03323
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03323> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1541-0420.2008.01049.x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "false positives per image"@en ,
                                                    "falsos positivos por imagen"@es ,
                                                    "每张图像的假阳性数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FPPI"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The false positives per image metric quantifies the average number of incorrect positive detections produced per image in an evaluation dataset. It is unbounded above and increases as a system generates more false alarms, making lower values preferable. It is most informative when reported alongside sensitivity, as in free-response ROC analysis, where it serves as the x-axis variable to indicate the trade-off between detection sensitivity and the frequency of false detections."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03324
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03324> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "positive predictive value"@en ,
                                                    "valor predictivo positivo"@es ,
                                                    "阳性预测值"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "PPV"@en ,
                                                       "precision"@en ,
                                                       "precisión"@es ,
                                                       "精确率"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition """Positive predictive value is the proportion of correctly identified positive cases among all cases predicted as positive by a model or test. It represents the probability that a positive prediction corresponds to a true positive outcome, and its value depends on the prevalence of the condition being tested as well as the model’s specificity and sensitivity.

                                         PPV = TP / (TP + FP)"""@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000416" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03325
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03325> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "negative predictive value"@en ,
                                                    "valor predictivo negativo"@es ,
                                                    "阴性预测值"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NPV"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """Negative predictive value denotes the proportion of negative predictions that correspond to actual negative cases. It reflects the reliability of negative results and depends on both test performance and outcome prevalence. It is often reported alongside sensitivity and specificity.

                                         NPV = TN / (TN + FN)"""@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000619" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03326
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03326> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03357> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1002/9780470317082> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "positive likelihood ratio"@en ,
                                                    "razón de verosimilitud positiva"@es ,
                                                    "阳性似然比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "LR+"@en ,
                                                       "PLR"@en ,
                                                       "positive LR"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """Positive Likelihood Ratio expresses how much more likely a positive test result is in individuals with the condition compared to those without it. It is calculated as the ratio of sensitivity to one minus specificity. Higher values indicate stronger evidence for the presence of the condition.

                                         LR+ = sensitivity / (1-specificity)"""@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000411" .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03327
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03327> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1109/CVPR.2019.00963> ;
                                         rdfs:label "calidad panóptica"@es ,
                                                    "panoptic quality"@en ,
                                                    "全景质量"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "PQ"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Panoptic quality evaluates panoptic segmentation by integrating instance detection accuracy with segmentation precision into a single metric. It calculates the sum of intersection-over-union values for correctly matched segments, normalized by the total number of matches and weighted penalties for false positives and false negatives. This metric provides a class-balanced measure of overall scene understanding, decomposable into segmentation quality and recognition quality components."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03328
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03328> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1145/1148170.1148262> ;
                                         rdfs:label "average precision"@en ,
                                                    "precisión promedio"@es ,
                                                    "平均精度"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AP"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Average precision summarizes the precision-recall curve as a single value, representing the area under this curve through an interpolated integration. It reflects how well a model maintains high precision while increasing recall across different decision thresholds, making it especially useful for imbalanced datasets where true negatives dominate. Unlike metrics based on the receiver operating characteristic curve, average precision focuses exclusively on the relationship between precision and recall, ignoring true negatives to emphasize performance on positive cases."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03329
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03329> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1198/016214506000001437> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Brier score"@en ,
                                                    "Brier 分数"@zh ,
                                                    "puntuación de Brier"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brier_score> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "BS"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Brier score quantifies the accuracy of probabilistic predictions by computing the mean squared difference between predicted probabilities and the actual binary outcomes. It captures both the ability of a model to discriminate between events and non-events and the degree to which predicted probabilities reflect observed frequencies. Scores range from 0 for perfect predictions to higher values for less accurate forecasts."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03330
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03330> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.5555/954544> ;
                                         rdfs:label "class error"@en ,
                                                    "error de clase"@es ,
                                                    "分类错误"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "classification error"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Classification error quantifies the proportion of samples incorrectly assigned to a class by a classifier. It is calculated as the number of misclassified samples divided by the total number of samples evaluated, representing the complement of accuracy. Lower values indicate better classification performance, while higher values signify more frequent misclassifications."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03331
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03331> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1910.12656> ;
                                         rdfs:label "class-wise calibration error"@en ,
                                                    "error de calibración por clase"@es ,
                                                    "按类别划分的校准误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CWCE"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Class-wise calibration error measures the alignment between predicted probabilities and observed outcomes for each class individually. It calculates the difference between confidence and accuracy across bins per class and aggregates these differences, optionally applying class-specific weights. Lower values indicate better marginal calibration across classes."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03332
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03332> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1609/aaai.v29i1.9602> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error de calibración esperado"@es ,
                                                    "expected calibration error"@en ,
                                                    "预期校准误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "ECE"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Expected calibration error estimates the average discrepancy between predicted confidence and actual accuracy for the predicted top class. It partitions predictions into bins and computes a weighted average of the differences between predicted and observed values, summarizing top-label calibration. Lower values reflect better overall calibration."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03333
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03333> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.5555/3454287.3455385> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error de calibración de kernel"@es ,
                                                    "kernel calibration error"@en ,
                                                    "核校准误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "KCE"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Kernel calibration error is a measure of canonical calibration error based on the maximum mean discrepancy between predicted probability distributions and true outcomes. It uses a matrix-valued kernel to capture differences across the entire probability space and provides an unbiased estimator of this discrepancy. This metric is primarily used for comparative calibration assessment, especially in settings with many classes or limited sample sizes."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03334
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03334> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4612-1524-0> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "logaritmo de verosimilitud negativo"@es ,
                                                    "negative log likelihood"@en ,
                                                    "负对数似然"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NLL"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Negative log likelihood quantifies the quality of probabilistic predictions by penalizing the log probability assigned to the correct class. It is a proper scoring rule that combines calibration and discrimination into a single metric, assigning larger penalties to overconfident incorrect predictions. Lower values correspond to more accurate and well-calibrated probability estimates."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03335
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03335> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1002/sim.3517> ;
                                         rdfs:label "observed-to-expected ratio"@en ,
                                                    "razón observado-esperado"@es ,
                                                    "观测值与预期值之比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "E/O ratio"@en ,
                                                       "O/E ratio"@en ,
                                                       "O:E ratio"@en ,
                                                       "observed:expected ratio"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The observed-to-expected ratio evaluates calibration by comparing the total number of observed events to the number of events predicted by a model within a specified time frame. A value of one indicates perfect calibration, while ratios greater than one suggest underprediction and values less than one indicate overprediction. This metric is widely used in risk prediction and survival analysis, often requiring adjustments for censoring to produce unbiased estimates."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03336
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03336> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03329> ;
                                         dc:source <https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.5555/3600270.3600897> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "puntuación de Brier raíz"@es ,
                                                    "root Brier score"@en ,
                                                    "均方根布里尔分数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "RBS"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The root Brier score is the square root of the Brier score, applicable in both binary and multiclass settings. It expresses the average magnitude of probabilistic prediction error on the same scale as the predicted probabilities, providing an interpretable measure of calibration and accuracy where lower values reflect better performance."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1.4142 .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03337
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03337> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.2307/1932409> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Dice similarity coefficient"@en ,
                                                    "Dice相似系数"@zh ,
                                                    "coeficiente de similitud de Dice"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "DSC"@en ,
                                                       "DSC"@zh ,
                                                       "DSC（Dice 相似系数）"@zh ,
                                                       "Dice"@en ,
                                                       "Dice coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Dice index"@en ,
                                                       "Dice score"@en ,
                                                       "Dice 相似度"@zh ,
                                                       "Dice 相似指数"@zh ,
                                                       "Dice 系数"@zh ,
                                                       "Dice 重叠度"@zh ,
                                                       "Dice 重叠系数"@zh ,
                                                       "Dice–Sørensen coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Dice–Sørensen score"@en ,
                                                       "Sørensen-Dice 系数"@zh ,
                                                       "Sørensen–Dice coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Sørensen–Dice score"@en ,
                                                       "Sørensen–Dice 系数"@zh ,
                                                       "coincidence index"@en ,
                                                       "索伦森–戴斯系数"@zh ,
                                                       "索伦森–迪斯系数"@zh ,
                                                       "索伦森系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "The Dice similarity coefficient quantifies the spatial overlap between two sets, such as predicted and reference segmentations, by calculating twice the size of their intersection divided by the sum of their sizes. It is mathematically equivalent to the F1 score when applied at the pixel level and ranges from 0 (no overlap) to 1 (perfect overlap). DSC is widely used in image segmentation evaluation to measure volumetric agreement and is closely related to the Jaccard index, with which it has a one-to-one correspondence."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03338
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03338> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03337> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1109/CVPR46437.2021.01629> ;
                                         rdfs:label "centerline Dice similarity coefficient"@en ,
                                                    "coeficiente de similitud de Dice de la línea central"@es ,
                                                    "中心线 Dice 相似系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "centerline DSC"@en ,
                                                       "clDSC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The centerline Dice similarity coefficient adapts the Dice formulation to assess segmentation quality for tubular or curvilinear structures by comparing the skeletons of the predicted and reference masks. It computes the harmonic mean of topology precision (fraction of predicted skeleton within the reference mask) and topology sensitivity (fraction of reference skeleton within the predicted mask), yielding a score between 0 and 1. It is designed to reflect both volumetric accuracy and preservation of structural connectivity."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03339
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03339> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "TPR = TP / (TP + FN)"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "tasa de verdaderos positivos"@es ,
                                                    "true positive rate"@en ,
                                                    "真阳性率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Se"@en ,
                                                       "Sens"@en ,
                                                       "TPF"@en ,
                                                       "TPR"@en ,
                                                       "exhaustividad"@es ,
                                                       "hit rate"@en ,
                                                       "potencia"@es ,
                                                       "probabilidad de detección"@es ,
                                                       "recall"@en ,
                                                       "sensibilidad"@es ,
                                                       "sensitivity"@en ,
                                                       "tasa de aciertos"@es ,
                                                       "true positive fraction"@en ,
                                                       "召回率"@zh ,
                                                       "灵敏度"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition """The true positive rate is the proportion of actual positive cases that a classifier or test correctly identifies as positive. It is calculated as the number of true positives divided by the sum of true positives and false negatives. This measure reflects how effectively a system detects the presence of the condition or class of interest.

                                         TPR = TP / (TP + FN)"""@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000233" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03340
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03340> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "tasa de verdaderos negativos"@es ,
                                                    "true negative rate"@en ,
                                                    "真阴性率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Sp"@en ,
                                                       "Spec"@en ,
                                                       "TNF"@en ,
                                                       "TNR"@en ,
                                                       "especificidad"@es ,
                                                       "selectivity"@en ,
                                                       "specificity"@en ,
                                                       "true negative fraction"@en ,
                                                       "特异性"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition """The true negative rate is the proportion of actual negative cases that are correctly identified as negative by a test or classifier. It quantifies a system’s ability to avoid false alarms by distinguishing true negatives from false positives. This measure is independent of disease or class prevalence and complements the true positive rate by capturing classification accuracy for the negative class.

                                         TNR = TN / (TN + FP)"""@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000134" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03341
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03341> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "average symmetric surface distance"@en ,
                                                    "distancia superficial simétrica promedio"@es ,
                                                    "平均对称表面距离"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "ASSD"@en ,
                                                       "weighted bilateral mean contour distance"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Average Symmetric Surface Distance calculates the mean of all shortest distances between boundary points of two segmentations, considering both directions equally. It evaluates the overall agreement of contour locations and provides a balanced view of segmentation accuracy. This metric is useful for applications where consistent boundary alignment is clinically important."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03342
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03342> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-8137.1912.tb05611.x> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "IoU = TP / (TP + FN + FP)"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "intersección sobre unión"@es ,
                                                    "intersection over union"@en ,
                                                    "交并比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CSI"@en ,
                                                       "Intersection over Union score"@en ,
                                                       "IoU"@en ,
                                                       "IoU coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "IoU score"@en ,
                                                       "Jaccard coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Jaccard index"@en ,
                                                       "Jaccard similarity coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Jaccard similarity coefficient score"@en ,
                                                       "TS"@en ,
                                                       "Tanimoto coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "critical success index"@en ,
                                                       "threat score"@en ,
                                                       "índice de Jaccard"@es ,
                                                       "índice de amenaza"@es ,
                                                       "índice de éxito crítico"@es ;
                                         skos:definition "Intersection over union quantifies the overlap between two regions by dividing the intersection by the union of the predicted and reference sets. It captures both false positives and false negatives by considering all pixels in either region. This metric is widely applied in segmentation and detection tasks to measure how comprehensively two regions coincide spatially."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03343
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03343> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03341> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1109/34.232073> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Hausdorff distance"@en ,
                                                    "distancia de Hausdorff"@es ,
                                                    "豪斯多夫距离"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "HD"@en ,
                                                       "Hausdorff metric"@en ,
                                                       "Pompeiu-Hausdorff distance"@en ,
                                                       "maximum symmetric surface distance"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Hausdorff distance quantifies the maximum boundary discrepancy between two sets of points by measuring the greatest distance from any point on one boundary to its closest point on the other boundary. It is commonly used to assess segmentation accuracy by focusing on worst-case spatial deviations. This metric is sensitive to outliers because a single distant point can dominate the result."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03345
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03345> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03669> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.2196/26151> ;
                                         rdfs:label "distancia de superficie normalizada"@es ,
                                                    "normalized surface distance"@en ,
                                                    "归一化表面距离"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NSD"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Normalized surface distance assesses segmentation quality by computing the proportion of surface points on both boundaries that lie within a specified tolerance distance from each other. It accounts for boundary uncertainty and allows user-defined flexibility through the tolerance parameter. This metric is particularly useful when annotation imprecision or clinically acceptable deviations need to be incorporated."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03346
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03346> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03342> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1109/CVPR46437.2021.01508> ;
                                         rdfs:label "boundary intersection over union"@en ,
                                                    "intersección de límites sobre unión"@es ,
                                                    "边界交并比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "boundary IoU"@en ,
                                                       "boundary intersection-over-union"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Boundary intersection over union measures alignment between predicted and reference regions by considering only pixels located within a fixed distance from their respective contours. It focuses exclusively on boundary accuracy and disregards interior areas beyond the defined margin. This metric is designed for tasks where precise delineation of edges or margins is critical."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03347
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03347> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03342> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-8137.1912.tb05611.x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "intersección de máscara sobre unión"@es ,
                                                    "mask intersection over union"@en ,
                                                    "掩码交并比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "mask IoU"@en ,
                                                       "mask intersection over union"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Mask intersection over union evaluates the overlap between two segmentation masks by comparing their shared area to the total area covered by either mask. It considers the entire region within both masks, providing a comprehensive measure of spatial agreement. This metric is commonly used in semantic and instance segmentation where pixel-level accuracy across the full object is important."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03348
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03348> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03342> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1469-8137.1912.tb05611.x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "box intersection over union"@en ,
                                                    "intersección de cajas delimitadoras sobre unión"@es ,
                                                    "框交并比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "box IoU"@en ,
                                                       "box intersection-over-union"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Box intersection over union quantifies the spatial overlap between two axis-aligned or oriented bounding boxes based on the ratio of their intersection to their union. It is applied in object detection to determine how well a predicted bounding box encloses the target structure. This metric reflects positional and scale accuracy without assessing fine object shape details."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03351
