###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03504
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03504> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04043> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1213/ANE.0000000000003653> ,
                                                   "Schober P, Vetter TR. Survival analysis and interpretation of time-to-event data: The tortoise and the hare. Anesth Analg 2018; 127(3):792-798."@en ;
                                         rdfs:comment "In survival analysis, time-to-event metrics refer to various statistical methods used to analyze time until an event occurs, such as failure or death. Common metrics include survival functions, hazard functions, and median survival times."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "rendimiento de análisis de tiempo hasta el evento"@es ,
                                                    "time-to-event analysis performance"@en ,
                                                    "事件发生时间"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "TTE metric"@en ,
                                                       "análisis de tiempo hasta el evento"@es ,
                                                       "time to event"@en ,
                                                       "time-to-event analysis"@en ,
                                                       "time-to-event analysis metric"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The performance of an AI model in terms of time-to-event analysis."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03508
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03508> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/12.2254742> ;
                                         rdfs:label "area under the precision-recall curve"@en ,
                                                    "área bajo la curva de precisión-exhaustividad"@es ,
                                                    "精确率-召回率曲线下的面积"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AUC_PR"@en ,
                                                       "AUPRC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The area under the precision-recall curve quantifies a model’s performance by summarizing the relationship between precision and recall across all classification thresholds. It captures the trade-off between identifying relevant positive cases and avoiding false positives, making it particularly informative for binary classification tasks with imbalanced class distributions. This metric is sensitive to the prevalence of the positive class and reflects how well a model maintains precision while maximizing recall."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000691> ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03510
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03510> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03656> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1177/001316446002000104> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Cohen's kappa"@en ,
                                                    "coeficiente kappa de Cohen"@es ,
                                                    "卡帕系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Cohen's κ"@en ,
                                                       "Kappa"@en ,
                                                       "Kappa 系数"@zh ,
                                                       "κ"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Cohen’s kappa measures the level of agreement between predicted and reference classifications while accounting for the agreement expected by chance. It provides a normalized score where 1 indicates perfect agreement, 0 indicates agreement equivalent to random chance, and negative values reflect agreement worse than chance. This metric is applicable to binary and multi-class classification and is more robust than simple accuracy in the presence of chance agreement."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000630" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03513
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03513> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03320> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.3115/1072064.1072067> ;
                                         rdfs:label "F2 score"@en ,
                                                    "F2 分数"@zh ,
                                                    "puntaje F2"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "F2"@en ,
                                                       "F2-score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "F2 score is a variant of the F(beta) score with β = 2, assigning greater weight to sensitivity than to precision. It is particularly useful in applications where identifying as many positive cases as possible is prioritized over minimizing false positives. This metric is often applied in medical and safety-critical domains where missed detections carry higher consequences."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03514
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03514> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03642> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03647> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1002/j.1538-7305.1948.tb01338.x> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1162/089976603321780272> ;
                                         rdfs:label "información mutua"@es ,
                                                    "mutual information"@en ,
                                                    "互信息"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MI"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Mutual information is a measure of the statistical dependence between two random variables, quantifying how much knowing one reduces the uncertainty about the other. It is defined in terms of entropy as the reduction in uncertainty of one variable given knowledge of the other, and can also be expressed as the Kullback–Leibler divergence between the joint distribution and the product of the marginals. It is always non-negative, symmetric, and equal to zero only when the variables are independent, making it a fundamental measure of shared information."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03515
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03515> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03514> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.3390/e19110631> ;
                                         rdfs:label "información mutua normalizada"@es ,
                                                    "normalized mutual information"@en ,
                                                    "归一化互信息"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NMI"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Normalized mutual information is a measure of similarity between two partitions that adjusts mutual information by the entropies of the partitions to ensure comparability. It rescales mutual information to fall between zero and one, where zero indicates no shared information and one indicates identical partitions. Different normalization schemes exist, but all serve to provide a scale-independent and symmetric evaluation of the agreement between clustering results."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03516
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03516> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03314> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1177/0272989x8900900307> ;
                                         rdfs:label "ROC曲线下的部分面积"@zh ,
                                                    "partial area under the receiver operator characteristic curve"@en ,
                                                    "área parcial bajo la curva ROC"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "pAUC"@en ,
                                                       "partial AUC"@en ,
                                                       "partial AUROC"@en ,
                                                       "partial area under the ROC curve"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The partial area under the receiver operating characteristic curve measures model performance within a predefined region of the ROC curve, typically corresponding to clinically relevant ranges such as high sensitivity or high specificity. It provides an average measure of sensitivity over a range of specificities or vice versa, offering a focused assessment of discrimination in critical operating conditions rather than across all thresholds. This metric is particularly useful when performance in specific regions is more important than overall discrimination."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000689" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03517
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03517> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0006-341X.2004.00187.x> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.2282011860> ;
                                         rdfs:label "percent agreement"@en ,
                                                    "porcentaje de concordancia"@es ,
                                                    "一致性百分比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "concordance rate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Percent agreement is the proportion of all evaluated cases in which a new test and a comparator yield the same result, whether both are positive or both are negative. It provides an overall measure of concordance between two methods but does not indicate accuracy relative to truth."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03518
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03518> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03517> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0006-341X.2004.00187.x> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.2282011860> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "Positive concordance rate refers to the percentage of cases where two different tests or assessments agree on a positive result. It's a measure of agreement, specifically focusing on the instances where both methods indicate a positive finding. [Kottler]"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "porcentaje de concordancia positiva"@es ,
                                                    "positive percent agreement"@en ,
                                                    "阳性一致性百分比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "PCR"@en ,
                                                       "PPA"@en ,
                                                       "positive concordance rate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Positive percent agreement is the proportion of comparator-positive cases that are also identified as positive by the new test. It quantifies agreement in the positive subset and is mathematically equivalent to sensitivity but is used specifically when the comparator is not a definitive reference standard."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03519
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03519> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03517> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0006-341X.2004.00187.x> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.2282011860> ;
                                         rdfs:label "negative percent agreement"@en ,
                                                    "porcentaje de concordancia negativa"@es ,
                                                    "阴性一致百分比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NPA"@en ,
                                                       "negative concordance rate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Negative percent agreement is the proportion of comparator-negative cases that are also identified as negative by the new test. It reflects agreement in the negative subset and corresponds mathematically to specificity, though it is distinguished in terminology when no true reference standard is available."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03520
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03520> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1002/1097-0142(1950)3:1%3C32::AID-CNCR2820030106%3E3.0.CO;2-3> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0127272> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Youden index"@en ,
                                                    "índice de Youden"@es ,
                                                    "约登指数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "informedness"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Youden index is a summary statistic used to evaluate the effectiveness of a diagnostic test by combining its sensitivity and specificity into a single measure. Defined as sensitivity + specificity – 1, it ranges from 0 (no discriminative ability) to 1 (perfect classification). The index is independent of disease prevalence, treats false positives and false negatives equally, and is widely applied to compare tests or to determine the optimal decision threshold on a receiver operating characteristic curve by maximizing the balance between sensitivity and specificity."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03523
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03523> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <http://doi.org/10.1177/1536867X0200200103> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Kendall's tau coefficient"@en ,
                                                    "coeficiente tau de Kendall"@es ,
                                                    "肯德尔等级相关系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Kendall's correlation coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Kendall’s τ"@en ,
                                                       "Kendall’s τ coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "tau"@en ,
                                                       "τ"@en ,
                                                       "肯德尔 τ 系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Kendall’s tau coefficient is a non-parametric statistic that measures the ordinal association between two ranked variables. It is calculated from the difference between the number of concordant and discordant observation pairs, with adjustments for tied ranks in some variants, and yields a value between −1 and 1. A value of 1 indicates perfect agreement in rank order, −1 indicates perfect inverse ordering, and 0 indicates no association in the rankings."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000240" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03524
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03524> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1002/(SICI)1097-0258(19960615)15:11%3C1199::AID-SIM218%3E3.0.CO;2-Y> ;
                                         rdfs:label "prediction probability"@en ,
                                                    "probabilidad de predicción"@es ,
                                                    "预测概率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "P_K"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Prediction probability quantifies the ability of an ordinal predictor to correctly rank cases across distinct outcome states. It represents the probability that, given two observations with different ordinal outcomes, the predictor assigns a higher value to the observation with the higher outcome, plus half the probability of tied predictor values. It generalizes the area under the ROC curve to multi-class ordinal settings without requiring dichotomization."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03525
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03525> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03652> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1213/ANE.0000000000002864> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.2307/1412159> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Spearman's rho"@en ,
                                                    "coeficiente de correlación de Spearman"@es ,
                                                    "斯皮尔曼秩相关系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Spearman rank correlation coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Spearman rho"@en ,
                                                       "Spearman rho coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "Spearman's rank correlation coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "rho"@en ,
                                                       "ro"@es ,
                                                       "ρ"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Spearman’s rho (ρ) is a nonparametric statistic that quantifies the strength and direction of a monotonic relationship between two variables. It is computed from the ranked values of the data rather than the raw values, making it suitable for ordinal data or continuous data that do not meet assumptions of linearity or normality. The coefficient ranges from –1 to +1, with values near the extremes indicating strong increasing or decreasing monotonic associations and values near zero indicating little to no monotonic correlation."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000201" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03526
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03526> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03307> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-41230-1_36> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "precisión entre los n mejores"@es ,
                                                    "top-n accuracy"@en ,
                                                    "前 n 名准确率"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Top-n accuracy measures the proportion of cases where the true answer appears within the first n predicted outputs of a system, regardless of order. It generalizes standard accuracy by treating inclusion within the top-n list as a success, rather than requiring the single top prediction to be correct. This metric is widely used in multi-class classification and question answering, reflecting realistic settings where users often examine several leading predictions rather than relying only on the first."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03527
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03527> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03652> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <http://doi.org/10.1142/S0218001411009093> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error absoluto medio"@es ,
                                                    "mean absolute error"@en ,
                                                    "平均绝对误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MAE"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Mean absolute error is a measure of prediction accuracy that calculates the average magnitude of the differences between predicted and true values. It is obtained by taking the absolute value of each individual error and averaging across all observations, which makes it straightforward to interpret since it is expressed in the same units as the target variable. It is commonly used in regression and ordinal classification tasks, providing a simple way to quantify overall error severity while being less sensitive to extreme outliers than squared-error measures."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03528
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03528> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03652> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <http://doi.org/10.1142/S0218001411009093> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error cuadrático medio"@es ,
                                                    "mean squared error"@en ,
                                                    "均方误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MSE"@en ,
                                                       "mean square error"@en ,
                                                       "mean-square error"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Mean squared error quantifies the average squared difference between estimated values and their corresponding reference values. It reflects both variance and bias in an estimator, serving as a measure of overall accuracy. Lower values indicate closer alignment between estimates and true values."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03531
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03531> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03637> ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03645> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04048>
                                                         ] ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/s11547-024-01886-9> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.220182> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "AFROC curve"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "alternative free-response receiver operating characteristic analysis"@en ,
                                                    "análisis alternativo de la curva ROC de respuesta libre"@es ,
                                                    "替代型自由响应受试者工作特征分析"@zh ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2019.1095> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AFROC"@en ,
                                                       "AFROC analysis"@en ,
                                                       "alternative free-response ROC"@en ,
                                                       "alternative free-response ROC analysis"@en ,
                                                       "alternative free-response operating characteristic analysis"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Alternative Free-Response Operating Characteristic (AFROC) analysis is an evaluation method for medical imaging systems, particularly those involving lesion detection. It plots per-lesion sensitivity versus 1 minus the specificity value on a per-image (or per-case) level while changing the threshold, allowing assessment of detection performance without a fixed number of response alternatives."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03532
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03532> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/TMI.2010.2072789> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "competition performance metric"@en ,
                                                    "métrica de rendimiento de la competición"@es ,
                                                    "竞争绩效指标"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CPM"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The competition performance metric summarizes the detection performance of a computer-aided detection system by averaging its sensitivities at a set of predefined false positive rates. It is derived from the free response operating characteristic curve, which relates sensitivity to the number of false positives per image. This metric provides a standardized single-value measure that emphasizes performance at low false positive rates, making it suitable for evaluating and comparing detection systems in clinically relevant conditions."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03533
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03533> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03637> ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03645> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03321>
                                                         ] ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03645> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03537>
                                                         ] ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/s11547-024-01886-9> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacr.2009.06.001> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.220182> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "FROC curve"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "análisis de la curva ROC de respuesta libre"@es ,
                                                    "free-response receiver operating characteristic analysis"@en ,
                                                    "自由响应受试者工作特征分析"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FROC"@en ,
                                                       "FROC analysis"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Free-Response Operating Characteristic (FROC) analysis evaluates imaging systems by plotting per-lesion sensitivity (true positive rate) against average number of false positives per image (or per case) while changing the threshold. Unlike ROC analysis which sets strict binary decisions at the level of image (or case) without lesion localization, free-response allows observers to indicate multiple potential lesions or findings per image."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03534
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03534> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1807.01696> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error de recuperación-precisión en la localización"@es ,
                                                    "location recall precision error"@en ,
                                                    "位置召回精度误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "LRP"@en ,
                                                       "location recall precision"@en ,
                                                       "location recall precision metric"@en ,
                                                       "location recall precision score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Localization recall precision is an evaluation metric for object detection that combines localization accuracy with precision and recall into a single interpretable error measure. It decomposes detector performance into three components: the tightness of predicted bounding boxes, the proportion of false positives, and the proportion of false negatives, each normalized to lie between zero and one. The overall score reflects the average per-object error, with lower values indicating better performance, and can be optimized at class-specific thresholds to provide more informative insights than traditional average precision."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03536
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03536> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03328> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1145/1148170.1148262> ;
                                         rdfs:label "mean average precision"@en ,
                                                    "precisión media promedio"@es ,
                                                    "平均精度"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "mAP"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Mean average precision is an evaluation metric that summarizes the effectiveness of a system across multiple queries or tasks by averaging the average precision values for each. It reflects the ability of a model to retrieve relevant items by considering both the precision and recall at various thresholds for every query, then aggregating these results into a single overall score."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03537
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03537> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "This measure captures the balance between correctly identifying targets and the burden of spurious detections by linking recall to a fixed false-positive operating level."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "sensibilidad a falsos positivos por imagen"@es ,
                                                    "sensitivity at false-positive per image"@en ,
                                                    "每张图像的假阳性率下的灵敏度"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Sensitivity at false-positives per image is a detection performance measure that quantifies the proportion of true findings correctly localized by a model when evaluated at a specified average number of false detections per image."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03538
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03538> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03343> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12880-015-0068-x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "average Hausdorff distance"@en ,
                                                    "distancia de Hausdorff promedio"@es ,
                                                    "平均豪斯多夫距离"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AHD"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Average Hausdorff distance computes the mean of directed distances between boundary points of two segmentations, offering a less outlier-sensitive alternative to the standard Hausdorff distance. It captures the overall similarity of boundaries rather than focusing solely on the most discrepant point. This metric is commonly used in segmentation evaluation where global contour alignment is of interest."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03540
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03540> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12880-015-0068-x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error de consistencia global"@es ,
                                                    "global consistency error"@en ,
                                                    "全局一致性误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "GCE"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Global consistency error measures segmentation consistency by aggregating voxel-level refinement errors between two regions. It accounts for hierarchical differences by evaluating whether one segmentation can be interpreted as a refinement of the other. This metric provides a symmetric score that penalizes structural inconsistencies while tolerating permissible refinements."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03541
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03541> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1093/biomet/75.4.731> ;
                                         rdfs:label "coeficiente de correlación intraclase"@es ,
                                                    "interclass correlation coefficient"@en ,
                                                    "类间相关系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "interclass correlation"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The interclass correlation coefficient is a statistical measure of resemblance between two related but distinct groups of observations. It quantifies the degree of linear association between paired measurements drawn from different classes, such as one set representing a source group and the other representing a related target group. Unlike the intraclass correlation coefficient, which captures similarity among members within the same class, the interclass correlation coefficient is designed to characterize cross-class relationships, making it particularly relevant in studies of inheritance, paired group comparisons, and other contexts where associations between distinct categories are of interest."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03542
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03542> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12880-015-0068-x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Mahalanobis distance"@en ,
                                                    "Mahalanobis 距离"@zh ,
                                                    "distancia de Mahalanobis"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MHD"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Mahalanobis Distance evaluates the separation between two sets of points by considering their covariance structure, thus reflecting correlations in the data. It measures the distance between the means of two point sets normalized by their combined variance. This metric is suited for assessing global shape differences in segmentation tasks rather than pointwise errors."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03544
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03544> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03647> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-540-45167-9_14> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jmva.2006.11.013> ;
                                         rdfs:label "variación de la información"@es ,
                                                    "variation of information"@en ,
                                                    "信息变异"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "VI"@en ,
                                                       "VOI"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The variation of information is an information-theoretic metric used to quantify the difference between two clusterings of the same dataset. It is defined in terms of Shannon entropy and mutual information, and measures the amount of information lost from one clustering and gained in moving to the other. The variation of information is non-negative, symmetric, and satisfies the triangle inequality, making it a true distance metric; it penalizes both over-splitting and merging of clusters, is sensitive to local changes, and allows consistent comparison of clustering solutions across datasets and algorithms."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03545
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03545> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03642> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12880-015-0068-x> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "The Rand index is a ratio, related to the notion of accuracy (STATO_0000415), which is used to compare the similarity of two clustering outcomes."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "Rand index"@en ,
                                                    "Rand 指数"@zh ,
                                                    "índice de Rand"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "RI"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Rand index quantifies the similarity between two data partitions by evaluating all possible pairs of elements and determining whether they are assigned consistently in both partitions. It considers agreements where pairs are placed in the same group or in different groups across both segmentations. Adjusted versions incorporate a correction for chance agreement, providing a normalized measure of clustering or segmentation consistency."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000592" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03546
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03546> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12880-015-0068-x> ;
                                         rdfs:label "similitud volumétrica"@es ,
                                                    "volumetric similarity"@en ,
                                                    "体积相似度"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "VS"@en ,
                                                       "立体相似度"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Volumetric similarity assesses agreement between two segmentations by measuring the absolute difference in their volumes relative to their combined size. It captures size-related discrepancies without considering positional alignment or boundary accuracy. This metric is particularly relevant when accurate volume estimation impacts clinical decision-making, such as tumor burden analysis."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03547
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03547> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/0005-2795(75)90109-9> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Matthews correlation coefficient"@en ,
                                                    "coeficiente de correlación de Matthews"@es ,
                                                    "马修斯相关系数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MCC"@en ,
                                                       "coeficiente phi"@es ,
                                                       "mean square contingency coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "phi"@en ,
                                                       "phi coefficient"@en ,
                                                       "φ"@en ,
                                                       "φ coefficient"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Matthews correlation coefficient evaluates the correlation between observed and predicted classifications, considering all four confusion matrix components. It provides a single summary score that reflects both correct and incorrect predictions across classes. It is regarded as a balanced metric even in the presence of class imbalance."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000524" ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


