                                                    "precision-recall curve"@en ,
                                                    "精确率-召回率曲线"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "P-R curve"@en ,
                                                       "PR curve"@en ,
                                                       "precision recall curve"@en ,
                                                       "precision-recall analysis"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The precision–recall curve (PRC) plots precision on the y-axis against recall on the x-axis at varying thresholds."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000695" .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03653
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03653> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12916-019-1466-7> ;
                                         rdfs:label "calibration slope"@en ,
                                                    "pendiente de calibración"@es ,
                                                    "校准斜率"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "The calibration slope assesses the spread of predicted probabilities by evaluating whether predictions are too extreme or too moderate. It is calculated as the slope in a logistic regression of observed outcomes on predicted log-odds, regardless of the method used to generate the predictions. A value of 1 indicates perfect calibration; values less than 1 suggest overconfident predictions, while values greater than 1 indicate underconfident predictions."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000687" .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03654
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03654> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1186/s12916-019-1466-7> ;
                                         rdfs:label "calibration intercept"@en ,
                                                    "ordenada en el origen de la calibración"@es ,
                                                    "校准截距"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "The calibration intercept is obtained from a logistic regression of observed outcomes on predicted log-odds and measures systematic bias in predicted probabilities, regardless of the method used to generate the predictions. An intercept of zero indicates perfect agreement; negative values indicate overestimation of risk, while positive values indicate underestimation."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000688" .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03655
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03655> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jclinepi.2015.12.005> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "calibración global"@es ,
                                                    "calibration-in-the-large"@en ,
                                                    "全局校准"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "mean calibration"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Calibration-in-the-large measures the overall agreement between predicted probabilities and observed event rates by comparing their means. It reflects systematic bias in predictions: a value near zero indicates no global overestimation or underestimation of risk. Large positive values suggest underprediction, while large negative values indicate overprediction."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03656
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03656> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2210.07810> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error de calibración esperado con estimación de densidad de núcleo"@es ,
                                                    "expected calibration error with kernel density estimate"@en ,
                                                    "基于核密度估计的预期校准误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "ECE-KDE"@en ,
                                                       "expected calibration error - kernel density estimate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Expected calibration error with kernel density estimate evaluates calibration by replacing binning with a kernel-based smoothing approach. It estimates the difference between predicted probabilities and observed outcomes across the entire probability space, providing a continuous measure of canonical calibration. Smaller values indicate closer alignment between predicted and true probabilities."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 2 .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03658
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03658> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03638> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1609/aaai.v29i1.9602> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error máximo de calibración"@es ,
                                                    "maximum calibration error"@en ,
                                                    "最大校准误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Maximum calibration error identifies the largest absolute difference between predicted probabilities and observed event frequencies across all bins. It provides a worst-case measure of local miscalibration, making it particularly relevant for high-stakes decision-making."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03659
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03659> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03640> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patrec.2008.08.010> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "macro average mean probability rate"@en ,
                                                    "tasa de probabilidad media promedio macro"@es ,
                                                    "宏平均平均概率率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MAPR"@en ,
                                                       "macro average probability rate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The macro average mean probability rate is a probabilistic performance metric for multi-class classification tasks where models output probability scores. It is calculated by averaging, across all classes, the mean predicted probability assigned to the true class for each instance, ensuring that each class contributes equally regardless of frequency. It provides a probability-based generalization of balanced accuracy, reflecting how well predicted probabilities align with true class membership, though it is sensitive to class imbalance."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03662
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03662> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03658> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1177/0272989X06295361> ;
                                         rdfs:label "beneficio neto"@es ,
                                                    "net benefit"@en ,
                                                    "净收益"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "NB"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Net benefit expresses the clinical utility of a prediction model by weighing the benefit of true positives against the harm of false positives under a chosen risk threshold. It reflects the net proportion of correct positive decisions after adjusting for unnecessary interventions. This metric is commonly used in decision-analytic frameworks."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03663
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03663> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03641> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016%2FS0140-6736%2886%2990837-8> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.11613/BM.2015.015> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Bland-Altman analysis"@en ,
                                                    "Bland-Altman 分析"@zh ,
                                                    "análisis de Bland-Altman"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bland%E2%80%93Altman_plot> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "B&A"@en ,
                                                       "B&A plot"@en ,
                                                       "Bland-Altman plot"@en ,
                                                       "Tukey mean-difference plot"@en ,
                                                       "difference plot"@en ,
                                                       "mean-difference plot"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "A Bland–Altman plot (difference plot) in biomedicine is a method of data plotting used in analyzing the agreement between two different tests. It is identical to a Tukey mean-difference plot."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03666
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03666> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/s11547-024-01886-9> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.3348/kjr.2022.0741> ;
                                         rdfs:label "diagnostic yield"@en ,
                                                    "rendimiento diagnóstico"@es ,
                                                    "诊断检出率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "DY"@en ,
                                                       "detection rate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Diagnostic yield represents the proportion of patients in a study cohort who are correctly identified as having the target condition by the test under evaluation. It is calculated as the number of true positive cases divided by the total number of individuals examined. This metric provides a clinically relevant estimate of how often a test detects the disease within the tested population, particularly useful in screening or diagnostic studies where negative cases are not fully verified."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03667
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03667> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "point inside mask/box/approximation"@en ,
                                                    "punto dentro de la máscara/caja/aproximación"@es ,
                                                    "掩码/框/近似区域内的点"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Point inside mask/box/approximation verifies whether a predicted point falls within the spatial bounds of a reference region, bounding box, or geometric approximation. It provides a binary outcome and does not account for proximity to boundaries or the degree of inclusion. This metric is primarily employed for coarse localization validation in detection systems."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> "false"^^xsd:boolean ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> "true"^^xsd:boolean .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03668
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03668> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-17711-8_23> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ;
                                         rdfs:label "center distance"@en ,
                                                    "distancia al centro"@es ,
                                                    "中心距离"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Center distance measures the spatial difference between the predicted center point of an object and its reference center, typically using Euclidean distance. The center can be defined as the geometric center of a bounding box, the centroid of a binary mask, or the intensity-weighted center of mass within an image. Lower values indicate closer alignment between predicted and reference positions, and predictions may be considered correct if the distance falls below a predefined threshold."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03669
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03669> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1111/jmi.12186> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "distancia media de la superficie"@es ,
                                                    "mean average surface distance"@en ,
                                                    "平均表面距离"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MASD"@en ,
                                                       "mean absolute surface distance"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Mean average surface distance measures the average of minimum distances from boundary points of one segmentation to another, aggregated in both directions. Unlike symmetric measures, it emphasizes the mean discrepancy across the entire contour rather than extreme deviations. It is typically applied to quantify contour-level differences in segmentation tasks."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03670
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03670> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03653> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/s11547-024-01886-9> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0077089> ;
                                         rdfs:label "contrast-to-noise ratio"@en ,
                                                    "relación contraste-ruido"@es ,
                                                    "对比噪声比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CNR"@en ,
                                                       "contrast to noise"@en ,
                                                       "contrast to noise ratio"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Contrast-to-noise ratio measures the ability to distinguish two regions of interest by comparing the difference in their signal intensities relative to the level of noise. It reflects the detectability of contrast features in the presence of noise, providing a more task-specific quality metric than signal-to-noise ratio. Higher contrast-to-noise ratio values indicate better contrast discrimination under noisy conditions."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03671
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03671> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03645> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1109/TIP.2003.819861> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1109/TIP.2011.2173206> ;
                                         rdfs:label "structural similarity index measure"@en ,
                                                    "índice de similitud estructural"@es ,
                                                    "结构相似性指数度量"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "SSIM"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The structural similarity index measure is a full-reference image quality metric that quantifies the similarity between two images by jointly comparing luminance, contrast, and structural information. It is computed locally over image patches, with values typically averaged to produce a global score between 0 and 1, where higher values indicate greater structural fidelity. Unlike error-based measures, the structural similarity index is designed to align with human perception by emphasizing preservation of spatial patterns and structural relationships."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03672
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03672> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/s11547-024-01886-9> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1904.09675> ;
                                         rdfs:label "BERTScore"@en ,
                                                    "BERTScore"@es ,
                                                    "BERT评分"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "BERT score"@en ,
                                                       "BERT-Score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "BERTScore is an automatic metric for evaluating text generation quality by measuring semantic similarity between a candidate text and a reference text using contextualized embeddings from pre-trained language models such as BERT or RoBERTa. It computes pairwise cosine similarity between token embeddings, applies greedy matching to identify the most similar tokens in each direction, and aggregates these similarities into precision, recall, and F1 scores, with the F1 score commonly used as the default. By relying on meaning-based vector representations rather than exact token or n-gram matches, BERTScore captures paraphrases and long-range dependencies, making it more robust to surface variation and better aligned with human judgments; the specific score depends on the choice of underlying language model."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03673
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03673> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03651> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.21236/ADA006655> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Flesch reading ease score"@en ,
                                                    "Flesch 阅读易读性分数"@zh ,
                                                    "Índice de legibilidad de Flesch"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Flesch reading ease"@en ,
                                                       "Flesch‐Kincaid readability index"@en ,
                                                       "Flesch‐Kincaid readability score"@en ,
                                                       "RE"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Flesch reading ease score is a readability metric that rates text on a scale from 0 to 100, where higher scores indicate easier comprehension. It is calculated from the average sentence length in words and the average number of syllables per word, producing values that can be mapped to approximate U.S. school grade levels. The score is widely used to assess how easily a general audience can read and understand written material."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 100. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 100. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03674
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03674> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03651> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.21236/ADA006655> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Flesch-Kincaid grade level"@en ,
                                                    "Flesch-Kincaid 年级水平"@zh ,
                                                    "nivel de grado Flesch-Kincaid"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "F-K grade level"@en ,
                                                       "F-K reading grade level"@en ,
                                                       "FKGL"@en ,
                                                       "Flesch-Kincaid reading grade level"@en ,
                                                       "Flesch–Kincaid reading level"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Flesch–Kincaid Grade Level is a readability metric that estimates the U.S. school grade level required to understand a text. It is calculated from the average sentence length in words and the average number of syllables per word, producing a direct numerical grade level without the need for conversion from another scale. The metric is widely used to match written material to the reading abilities of a target audience."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03676
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03676> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03646> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/s41592-023-02151-z> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1093/bioinformatics/btu080> ;
                                         rdfs:label "intersección sobre referencia"@es ,
                                                    "intersection over reference"@en ,
                                                    "交集与参考集之比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "IoR"@en ,
                                                       "pixel-level sensitivity"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Intersection over reference measures the fraction of the reference region that overlaps with the prediction by normalizing the intersection size to the reference size. It reflects how completely the target structure is captured without penalizing for excessive prediction beyond the reference boundary. This metric is useful when coverage of the reference anatomy is more critical than minimizing false positives."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03678
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03678> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03649> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03652> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.5194/gmd-15-5481-2022> ;
                                         rdfs:label "error cuadrático medio"@es ,
                                                    "root mean squared error"@en ,
                                                    "均方根误差"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "RMSE"@en ,
                                                       "root mean square error"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Root mean squared error is a statistical measure that quantifies the average magnitude of prediction errors by taking the square root of the mean of squared differences between observed and predicted values. It expresses errors in the same units as the original data, which makes the metric directly interpretable as a typical deviation. It penalizes larger errors more heavily than smaller ones, and under the assumption of normally distributed independent errors, minimizing it corresponds to finding the most likely model fit."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03679
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03679> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1098/rsta.2008.0043> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "area under the predictive receiver operating characteristic curve"@en ,
                                                    "área bajo la curva característica operativa del receptor predictivo"@es ,
                                                    "预测接收者操作特征曲线下的面积"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AUC-PROC"@en ,
                                                       "AUPROC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The area under the predictive receiver operating characteristic curve evaluates the overall quality of probabilistic predictions in binary classification by plotting positive predictive value against negative predictive value across thresholds. Unlike the traditional receiver operating characteristic curve, this approach conditions on the predicted outcome and incorporates the prevalence of the condition in the population. The area under this curve reflects the model’s average predictive validity across different decision thresholds and is particularly useful when the focus is on the reliability of predictions rather than classification accuracy."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03680
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03680> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03314> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patrec.2005.10.010> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "AUC de cada clase frente a cada una de las otras k-1 clases"@es ,
                                                    "AUC of each class vs. each of the other k-1 classes"@en ,
                                                    "每个类别与其余 k-1 个类别之间的 AUC"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AU1P"@en ,
                                                       "AU1U"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "This metric extends the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve to multi-class classification by computing the AUC for each class against every other class in a pairwise manner and then averaging the results. It can be calculated as an unweighted mean of all pairwise AUCs (AU1U) or as a weighted mean based on class prevalence (AU1P). This approach provides a comprehensive measure of a model’s discriminative ability across all classes while accounting for potential class imbalance when using the weighted version."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03681
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03681> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03314> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patrec.2008.08.010> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "AUC de cada clase frente al resto combinadas"@es ,
                                                    "AUC of each class vs. the rest combined"@en ,
                                                    "每个类别与其余所有类别组合之间的 AUC"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "AUNP"@en ,
                                                       "AUNU"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "This metric generalizes the area under the receiver operating characteristic curve to multi-class classification by computing the AUC for each class treated as positive against all remaining classes combined as negative, then averaging these values. It can be calculated as an unweighted mean assuming equal class importance (AUNU) or as a weighted mean based on class prevalence (AUNP). This approach provides an overall assessment of a model’s ability to discriminate each class from all others while offering flexibility to account for true class distribution when using the weighted version."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03682
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03682> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03637> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jacr.2009.06.001> ,
                                                   "He X, Frey E. ROC, LROC, FROC, AFROC: an alphabet soup. J Am Coll Radiol 2009; 6(9):652-5."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "análisis de la curva característica operativa del receptor de localización"@es ,
                                                    "localization receiver operating characteristic analysis"@en ,
                                                    "定位受试者工作特征分析"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "LROC"@en ,
                                                       "localization ROC"@en ,
                                                       "location ROC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Localization ROC (LROC) curve plots location recall (i.e., rate of true positive decisions with correct localization) values against the false positive rate (1 − specificity) as the classification threshold varies. The area under the LROC curve provides an overall measure of performance across all thresholds."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03683
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03683> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.acra.2005.05.013> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Obuchowski index"@en ,
                                                    "Obuchowski 指数"@zh ,
                                                    "índice de Obuchowski"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "weighted average of AUROC"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Obuchowski index is a nonparametric measure of diagnostic accuracy that generalizes the area under the ROC curve (AUC) to settings where the reference standard is continuous, ordinal, or nominal. It estimates the probability that a subject with a higher reference standard value receives a higher test score, averaging results from all relevant category or value pairs with optional weighting and penalties to reflect the clinical importance of different misclassifications. When the reference standard is binary, the Obuchowski index reduces to the conventional ROC AUC."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03684
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03684> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03637> ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03645> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03222>
                                                         ] ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.3348/kjr.2021.0223> ;
                                         rdfs:comment "The summary metrics include AUROC at each time point and an integrated AUC (iAUC), which is a mathematical integration of multiple time-dependent AUC values across the follow-up period."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "análisis de la curva ROC dependiente del tiempo"@es ,
                                                    "time-dependent receiver operating characteristic analysis"@en ,
                                                    "时间依赖性受试者工作特征分析"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "time-dependent ROC analysis"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Time-dependent receiver operating characteristic (ROC) analysis refers to a set of ROC analyses performed at specific follow-up time points in time-to-event prediction. It typically involves multiple ROC analyses, each corresponding to a distinct time point during the follow-up period. For each time point, a separate ROC curve and its corresponding area under the curve (AUC) are generated. As a result, the ROC curves and their AUC values are provided as a function of time."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03687
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03687> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03655> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1128/AAC.48.8.2787-2792.2004> ;
                                         rdfs:label "cociente de riesgos"@es ,
                                                    "hazard ratio"@en ,
                                                    "风险比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "HR"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The hazard ratio is a measure of relative risk that compares the hazard, or instantaneous event rate, between two groups in time-to-event analysis. It expresses the ratio of the likelihood that an event will occur at a given time point in one group relative to another, typically estimated using the Cox proportional hazards model. A hazard ratio greater than one indicates a higher event rate in the treatment group, less than one indicates a lower rate, and equal to one indicates no difference, under the assumption that the ratio remains constant over time."@en ;
                                         skos:exactMatch "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000677" .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03688
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03688> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03655> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03704> ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03645> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03223>
                                                         ] ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03645> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03572>
                                                         ] ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.3348/kjr.2021.0223> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Kaplan-Meier estimator"@en ,
                                                    "estimador de Kaplan-Meier"@es ,
                                                    "卡普兰 - 迈耶估计量"@zh ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaplan%E2%80%93Meier_estimator> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "K-M curve"@en ,
                                                       "K-M plot"@en ,
                                                       "KM估计量"@zh ,
                                                       "Kaplan-Meier curve"@en ,
                                                       "Kaplan-Meier plot"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Kaplan–Meier estimator, also known as the product limit estimator, is a non-parametric statistic used to estimate the survival function from lifetime data. In medical research, it is often used to measure the fraction of patients living for a certain amount of time after treatment."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03689
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03689> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03655> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03641> ;
                                         rdfs:label "modelo de riesgo paramétrico"@es ,
                                                    "parametric hazard model"@en ,
                                                    "参数风险模型"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Parametric hazard models are survival analysis techniques that assume a specific, underlying probability distribution (e.g., Weibull, exponential) for event times. Unlike nonparametric methods (Kaplan-Meier), they define a smooth hazard function, allowing for efficient estimation of parameters, prediction of future survival, and better handling of complex patterns."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03690
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03690> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03657> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "fracción de casos con ajuste por parte del usuario"@es ,
                                                    "fraction of cases with user adjustment"@en ,
                                                    "用户调整病例的比例"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Fraction of cases with user adjustment measures the proportion of outputs from an algorithm that require manual correction by a human operator. It serves as an indicator of the algorithm’s practical accuracy and reliability from a user perspective. Lower values suggest greater autonomy of the system."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03691
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03691> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03657> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "tiempo para el ajuste por parte del usuario"@es ,
                                                    "time for user adjustment"@en ,
                                                    "用户调整时间"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Time for user adjustment reflects the duration required to manually review and modify an algorithm’s outputs before acceptance. It provides insight into the usability and efficiency of the system in a clinical setting. Longer times may indicate higher interaction burden or workflow inefficiency."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03692
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03692> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03657> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1117/1.JMI.11.2.024504> ;
                                         rdfs:label "incertidumbre asociada a la interacción con el usuario"@es ,
                                                    "uncertainty associated with user interaction"@en ,
                                                    "与用户交互相关的不确定性"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Uncertainty associated with user interaction describes the additional variability introduced when manual adjustments or user decisions affect an algorithm’s output. This measure accounts for operator-dependent factors in performance evaluation. It highlights the combined impact of algorithmic and human components on overall reliability."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03693
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03693> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patter.2023.100802> ;
                                         rdfs:label "RadCliQ"@en ,
                                                    "RadCliQ"@es ,
                                                    "放射学报告临床质量"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "RadCliQ-v1"@en ,
                                                       "Radiology Report Clinical Quality"@en ,
                                                       "Radiology Report Clinical Quality Metric"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "RadCliQ is a composite metric for evaluating automatically generated radiology reports, designed to align closely with radiologists’ assessments of report quality. It combines normalized scores from BLEU, BERTScore, CheXbert vector similarity, and RadGraph F1 using a constrained linear regression model that weights each metric to predict the total number of clinically significant and insignificant errors in a report. The resulting score reflects an interpretable, clinically oriented measure of report accuracy, with lower values indicating fewer predicted errors."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03696
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03696> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2004.09167> ;
                                         rdfs:label "SembScore"@en ,
                                                    "SembScore"@es ,
                                                    "SembScore 语义评分"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CheXbert labeler vector similarity"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "SembScore is a radiology-specific evaluation metric that measures the similarity of clinical findings between a generated report and a reference report. It uses the CheXbert labeler to extract a 14-dimensional indicator vector representing predefined pathologies from each report, then computes the cosine similarity between these vectors. The resulting score reflects the degree of alignment in reported medical conditions, providing a clinically focused assessment that is robust to differences in wording."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03697
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03697> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.patter.2023.100802> ,
                                                   <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2106.14463> ;
                                         rdfs:label "RadGraph-F1"@en ,
                                                    "RadGraph-F1"@es ,
                                                    "放射报告图谱 F1 分数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "F1-RadGraph"@en ,
                                                       "F1RadGraph"@en ,
                                                       "RadGraph F1"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "RadGraph F1 is a clinically oriented evaluation metric for radiology report generation that measures the overlap of medical entities and their relations between a generated report and a reference report. Both reports are parsed into structured knowledge graphs, where nodes represent clinical concepts and edges represent semantic relations, and matching is determined by identical token spans, entity types, and relation types. The final score is the average of the F1 scores for entity and relation matches, providing an assessment of both the content and structural accuracy of the generated report’s clinical information."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03698
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03698> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2406.16845> ;
                                         rdfs:label "RaTEScore"@en ,
                                                    "RaTEScore"@es ,
                                                    "放射学报告文本评估分数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "radiological report text evaluation metric"@en ,
                                                       "radiological report text evaluation score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "RaTEScore is an entity-aware metric for assessing the quality of automatically generated radiology reports. It evaluates alignment with reference reports by extracting clinically relevant entities, mapping synonyms into a shared semantic space, and weighting matches by clinical importance while accounting for negation differences. The score is computed as the harmonic mean of precision-like and recall-like measures over matched entities, providing a modality- and anatomy-agnostic assessment that is robust to terminology variation and sensitive to clinically significant distinctions."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03699
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03699> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2405.03595> ;
                                         rdfs:label "GREEN"@en ,
                                                    "GREEN"@es ,
                                                    "绿色"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "GREEN metric"@en ,
                                                       "GREEN score"@en ,
                                                       "Generative Radiology Report Evaluation and Error Notation"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "GREEN is an automated metric for assessing the factual accuracy of radiology reports by comparing a candidate report to a reference. It uses a language model to identify matched findings, detect and categorize clinically significant errors, and generate both a numerical score ranging from 0 to 1 and an explanatory summary. The score increases with more correct matches and fewer significant errors, while the summary provides interpretable feedback to support model evaluation and improvement."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03700
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03700> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03654> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2405.20613> ;
                                         rdfs:label "FineRadScore"@en ,
                                                    "FineRadScore"@es ,
                                                    "精细放射评分"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "FineRadScore is a large language model–based metric for evaluating AI-generated chest X-ray reports by comparing them to reference reports through minimal line-by-line corrections. It identifies the smallest set of insertions, deletions, or substitutions needed to match the reference, assigns each correction a severity rating reflecting clinical urgency, and classifies the type of error. The metric produces fine-grained, interpretable outputs that capture both textual accuracy and clinical significance, enabling detailed assessment beyond a single aggregate score."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03703
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03703> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03651> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.21236/ADA006655> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Gunning Fog index"@en ,
                                                    "Gunning Fog 指数"@zh ,
                                                    "índice de Gunning Fog"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Fog index"@en ,
                                                       "Fog score"@en ,
                                                       "GF"@en ,
                                                       "GFOG"@en ,
                                                       "Gunning Fog"@en ,
                                                       "Gunning Fog score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Gunning Fog index is a readability metric that estimates the U.S. school grade level needed to understand a text on first reading. It is calculated from the average sentence length in words and the percentage of complex words—defined as those with three or more syllables, excluding proper nouns, compound words, familiar jargon, and common suffix forms. Higher scores indicate greater reading difficulty, with values of 8–10 considered appropriate for general audiences and values above 17 indicating very complex material."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03704
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03704> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03651> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03641> ,
                                                         [ rdf:type owl:Restriction ;
                                                           owl:onProperty <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03645> ;
                                                           owl:someValuesFrom <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00156>
                                                         ] ;
                                         rdfs:label "Fry graph"@en ,
                                                    "Fry 可读性图表"@zh ,
                                                    "gráfico de Fry"@es ;
                                         rdfs:seeAlso <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fry_readability_formula> ;
                                         skos:altLabel "Fry readability formula"@en ,
                                                       "Fry readability graph"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Fry readability graph is a readability metric for English texts."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03705
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03705> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03651> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1080/19325037.2008.10599016> ,
                                                   <https://www.jstor.org/stable/40011226> ;
                                         rdfs:label "SMOG index"@en ,
                                                    "SMOG指数"@zh ,
                                                    "índice SMOG"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "McLaughlin SMOG index"@en ,
                                                       "SMOG"@en ,
                                                       "SMOG score"@en ,
                                                       "simple measure of gobbledygook"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The SMOG index is a readability metric that estimates the years of formal education required for full comprehension of a text. It is calculated by counting the number of polysyllabic words in a 30-sentence sample, taking the square root of this count, and adding three to yield the SMOG grade level. Developed for accuracy and simplicity, it is widely used in health communication to ensure written materials are accessible to target audiences."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 4. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03706
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03706> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03651> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1002/pits.21740> ;
                                         rdfs:label "FORCAST readability estimate"@en ,
                                                    "FORCAST 可读性估计"@zh ,
                                                    "estimación de legibilidad de FORCAST"@es ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FORCAST"@en ,
                                                       "FORCAST readability formula"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The FORCAST readability formula estimates the reading grade level of a text based on the number of single-syllable words in a 150-word sample. It is designed for materials that may not contain complete sentences, such as lists, instructions, or technical documents, and does not incorporate sentence length or syntactic complexity. The formula produces grade-level estimates of 5 or higher, making it most applicable to adult-oriented, non-narrative content such as manuals, forms, and questionnaires."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 5. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 20. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03707
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03707> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "marcabilidad"@es ,
                                                    "markedness"@en ,
                                                    "标记度 "@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "MK"@en ,
                                                       "delta P"@en ,
                                                       "delta-P"@en ,
                                                       "deltaP"@en ,
                                                       "Δp"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """Markedness is a metric that quantifies the reliability of predictions by combining positive predictive value and negative predictive value. It is defined as the sum of these two predictive values minus one, producing a score that ranges from –1 to +1. A value of +1 indicates perfectly trustworthy predictions, 0 corresponds to chance-level performance, and negative values indicate systematically misleading predictions; however, the measure is sensitive to class prevalence and can be unstable in imbalanced datasets.

                                         MK = PPV + NPV - 1"""@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> -1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03708
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03708> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.aci.2018.08.003"@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "balanced error rate"@en ,
                                                    "tasa de error equilibrada"@es ,
                                                    "平衡错误率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "BER"@en ,
                                                       "HTER"@en ,
                                                       "half total error rate"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Balanced error rate measures the average of the false positive rate and the false negative rate, giving equal weight to both types of errors. It is conceptually the counterpart of the balanced accuracy (balanced classification rate), emphasizing error rather than correct classification, and is particularly useful for imbalanced datasets where overall accuracy can be misleading. Lower values indicate better performance, with zero representing perfect classification and one representing the worst case."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


