###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04073
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04073> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/S0895-4356(03)00177-X> ;
                                         rdfs:label "cociente de probabilidades diagnóstico"@es ,
                                                    "diagnostic odds ratio"@en ,
                                                    "诊断优势比"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "DOR"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """The diagnostic odds ratio is a single summary measure of diagnostic test accuracy, defined as the ratio of the odds of a positive test result in diseased individuals to the odds of a positive result in non-diseased individuals. It combines sensitivity and specificity into one statistic, making it mathematically equivalent to the ratio of positive to negative likelihood ratios. A value of 1 indicates no discriminatory ability, values greater than 1 reflect increasing diagnostic accuracy, and values less than 1 suggest systematic misclassification, while remaining independent of disease prevalence.

                                         DOR = ⁠LR+ / LR−"""@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04074
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04074> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.2307/2288117> ;
                                         rdfs:label "Fowlkes-Mallows index"@en ,
                                                    "índice de Fowlkes-Mallows"@es ,
                                                    "福尔克斯 - 马洛指数"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FM"@en ,
                                                       "FM 指数"@zh ,
                                                       "FMI"@en ,
                                                       "Fowlkes Mallows index"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The Fowlkes–Mallows index measures the similarity between two data clusterings by comparing how object pairs are grouped. It is defined as the number of pairs placed in the same cluster in both partitions divided by the geometric mean of the number of pairs in the same cluster in each partition separately. The index ranges from 0 (no shared pairwise groupings) to 1 (identical pairwise groupings) and can be applied to both fixed-k partitions and hierarchical clustering comparisons."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04075
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04075> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04043> ;
                                         rdfs:comment """Examples:
                                         - Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
                                         - Mean Squared Error (MSE)
                                         - Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
                                         - R² (R-Squared)"""@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "regression performance"@en ,
                                                    "rendimiento de regresión"@es ,
                                                    "回归"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "regresión"@es ,
                                                       "regression"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Regression models have continuous output; a regression metric measures some sort of distance between predictions and reference standard."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04077
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04077> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04043> ;
                                         rdfs:label "image processing performance"@en ,
                                                    "rendimiento de procesamiento de imágenes"@es ,
                                                    "图像处理"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "image processing"@en ,
                                                       "procesamiento de imágenes"@es ;
                                         skos:definition "A metric used to measure the quality of image manipulation, such as reconstruction, compression, noise reduction, or signal enhancement."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04078
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04078> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03593> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.2214/AJR.25.34340> ;
                                         rdfs:comment """Enhanced Detection Rate (EDR) can be measured in two ways: relative EDR (EDRr) and absolute EDR (EDRa).  The key difference lies in the denominator, while both metrics share the same numerator—the number of exams (retrospective metric) detected by the AI model but not reported in the radiology report.

                                         For EDRr, the denominator is the total number of exams detected by the radiologist, representing the relative percentage improvement in sensitivity for the \"average radiologist.\"  The denominator for the EDRa is the total number of exams reviewed.  

                                         - Nina Kottler"""@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "absolute enhanced detection rate"@en ,
                                                    "tasa absoluta de detección mejorada"@es ,
                                                    "绝对增强检出率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "EDRa"@en ,
                                                       "aEDR"@en ,
                                                       "absolute EDR"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The absolute enhanced detection rate is defined as the ratio between the number of enhanced detection cases and total number of cases (i.e., potential of AI to increase radiologist detection of positive cases relative to all examined cases)."@en ,
                                                         """The absolute enhanced detection rate is the proportion of true positive findings uniquely detected by artificial intelligence out of the total number of examinations in the evaluated cohort. It provides a population-level perspective by quantifying the overall increase in diagnostic yield attributable to artificial intelligence. This measure is especially relevant in public health and screening contexts.

                                         aEDR = (number of positive cases not detected by human alone) / (total number of cases)"""@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04079
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04079> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03593> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.2214/AJR.25.34340> ;
                                         rdfs:comment """Enhanced Detection Rate (EDR) can be measured in two ways: relative EDR (EDRr) and absolute EDR (EDRa).  The key difference lies in the denominator, while both metrics share the same numerator—the number of exams (retrospective metric) detected by the AI model but not reported in the radiology report.

                                         For EDRr, the denominator is the total number of exams detected by the radiologist, representing the relative percentage improvement in sensitivity for the \"average radiologist.\" The denominator for the EDRa is the total number of exams reviewed.  

                                         - Nina Kottler"""@en ,
                                                      "The relative enhanced detection rate is defined as the ratio between the number of enhanced detection cases and number of radiologist true-positive cases (i.e., potential of AI to increase radiologist detection of positive cases relative to radiologist true-positives without AI assistance)."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "relative enhanced detection rate"@en ,
                                                    "tasa relativa de detección mejorada"@es ,
                                                    "相对增强检测率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "EDRr"@en ,
                                                       "rEDR"@en ,
                                                       "relative EDR"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """The relative enhanced detection rate expresses the proportion of true positive findings uniquely identified by artificial intelligence in relation to the number of positive findings detected by the human reader. It provides a radiologist-centered perspective by quantifying the percentage improvement in sensitivity when artificial intelligence is added. This metric is particularly suited to comparing the benefit of artificial intelligence relative to individual or average radiologist performance.

                                         rEDR = (number of positive cases not detected by human alone) / (number of positive human-detected cases)"""@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04080
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04080> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1186/1471-2105-9-303> ;
                                         rdfs:label "false discovery rate"@en ,
                                                    "tasa de descubrimiento falso"@es ,
                                                    "错误发现率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FDR"@en ;
                                         skos:definition """The false discovery rate is the expected proportion of false positives among all test results deemed significant or positive. Unlike more conservative measures such as the family-wise error rate, it controls the proportion rather than the absolute occurrence of false positives, making it particularly useful in large-scale or high-dimensional testing contexts. It serves as a key measure for balancing discovery power with error control in statistical inference and diagnostic decision-making.

                                         FDR = FP / (TP + FP) = 1 - PPV"""@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04081
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04081> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03639> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijid.2021.04.004> ;
                                         rdfs:label "false omission rate"@en ,
                                                    "tasa de falsas omisiones"@es ,
                                                    "漏检率"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FOR"@en ,
                                                       "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/STATO_0000220" ;
                                         skos:definition """The false omission rate is the proportion of individuals with negative test results who are in fact positive for the condition being tested. It is mathematically defined as one minus the negative predictive value, representing the probability that a negative result is incorrect. It is sensitive to disease prevalence, remaining low when prevalence is low but increasing substantially when prevalence is high, thereby quantifying the risk of false reassurance from negative outcomes.

                                         FOR = FN / (TN + FN) = 1 - NPV"""@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04082
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04082> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03526> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-41230-1_36> ;
                                         rdfs:label "precisión entre los 10 mejores"@es ,
                                                    "top-10 accuracy"@en ,
                                                    "前 10 名准确率"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Top-10 accuracy measures the proportion of instances where the true class label appears within the top 10 predicted class labels, regardless of their order."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04086
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04086> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03655> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.3348/kjr.2021.0223> ;
                                         rdfs:label "log-risk score"@en ,
                                                    "puntuación de riesgo logarítmico"@es ,
                                                    "对数风险评分"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "log risk score"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The log-risk score is a time-independent linear predictor derived from the Cox proportional hazards model that represents an individual’s overall risk of experiencing an event, such as death or disease recurrence. It is computed as the weighted sum of patient covariates, where the weights are regression coefficients estimated from the model. Higher log-risk scores correspond to higher event risk, and while the score itself is not a probability, it can be transformed into time-dependent survival probabilities when combined with baseline survival estimates."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04087
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04087> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03655> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.1038/sj.bjc.6601118> ;
                                         rdfs:label "probabilidad de supervivencia"@es ,
                                                    "survival probability"@en ,
                                                    "生存概率"@zh ;
                                         skos:definition "Survival probability is the probability that an individual remains free of a specified event, such as death or relapse, beyond a given time point measured from the study origin. It is expressed by the survival function, which represents the cumulative likelihood of continuing survival up to time t, and forms the foundation of survival analysis. This measure is typically estimated with methods such as the Kaplan–Meier estimator, accommodates censoring, and provides clinically interpretable outcomes including median survival and fixed-time survival rates."@en ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00274> 1. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03651> 0. ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03652> 1. .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04088
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_04088> rdf:type owl:Class ;
                                         rdfs:subClassOf <https://rsna.org/roadmap#ROADMAP_03655> ,
                                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_03302> ;
                                         dc:source <https://doi.org/10.3348/kjr.2021.0223> ;
                                         rdfs:label "cumulative hazard"@en ,
                                                    "riesgo acumulado"@es ,
                                                    "累积风险"@zh ;
                                         skos:altLabel "CH"@en ,
                                                       "CHF"@en ,
                                                       "cumulative hazard function"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "The cumulative hazard is a time-dependent function in survival analysis that represents the total risk of an event occurring up to a given time point. It accumulates the instantaneous hazard over time and serves as the mathematical basis for deriving survival probabilities. Many survival models, including proportional hazards models and random survival forests, estimate cumulative hazard as a primary output, which can then be used directly for risk assessment or transformed into survival probabilities and summary measures for model evaluation."@en .


#################################################################
#    Individuals
#################################################################

###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00170
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00170> rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00169> ;
                                         rdfs:comment """A1 : (Meta)data are retrievable by their identifier using a standardized communications protocol.
A1.1 : The protocol is open, free, and universally implementable.
A1.2 : The protocol allows for an authentication and authorization procedure, where necessary.
A2 : Metadata are accessible, even when the data are no longer available."""@en ,
                                                      "The A in FAIR: data and metadata are retrievable by their identifier using standardised protocols."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "accessibility"@en ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FAIR-A"@en ,
                                                       "accessibility principle"@en ,
                                                       "accessible"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Accessible: Once users finds the required data, they need to know how the data can be accessed, possibly including authentication and authorisation."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00171
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00171> rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00169> ;
                                         rdfs:comment """F1 : (Meta)data are assigned a globally unique and persistent identifier.
F2 : Data are described with rich metadata (defined by R1).
F3 : Metadata clearly and explicitly include the identifier of the data they describe.
F4 : (Meta)data are registered or indexed in a searchable resource."""@en ,
                                                      "The F in FAIR: data and metadata are assigned globally unique and persistent identifiers."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "findability"@en ;
                                         skos:altLabel "F"@en ,
                                                       "FAIR-F"@en ,
                                                       "findability principle"@en ,
                                                       "findable"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Findable: The first step in (re)using data is to find them. Metadata and data should be easy to find for both humans and computers. Machine-readable metadata are essential for automatic discovery of datasets and services."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00172
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00172> rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00169> ;
                                         rdfs:comment """I1 : (Meta)data use a formal, accessible, shared, and broadly applicable language for knowledge representation.
I2 : (Meta)data use vocabularies that follow FAIR principles.
I3 : (Meta)data include qualified references to other (meta)data."""@en ,
                                                      "The I in FAIR: data and metadata use a formal, accessible, shared, and broadly applicable language for knowledge representation."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "interoperability"@en ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FAIR-I"@en ,
                                                       "I"@en ,
                                                       "interoperability principle"@en ,
                                                       "interoperable"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Interoperable: Data should be able to integrate and work alongside other data systems. This means using shared, standard languages (like JSON or XML) and formal vocabularies so systems can exchange information seamlessly."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00173
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00173> rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00169> ;
                                         rdfs:comment """R1 : (Meta)data are richly described with a plurality of accurate and relevant attributes.
R1.1 : (Meta)data are released with a clear and accessible data usage license.
R1.2 : (Meta)data are associated with detailed provenance.
R1.3 : (Meta)data meet domain-relevant community standards."""@en ,
                                                      "The R in FAIR: data and metadata are richly described with a plurality of accurate and relevant attributes."@en ;
                                         rdfs:label "reuseability"@en ;
                                         skos:altLabel "FAIR-R"@en ,
                                                       "R"@en ,
                                                       "reusable"@en ,
                                                       "reuseability principle"@en ,
                                                       "reuseable"@en ;
                                         skos:definition "Reusable: The ultimate goal of FAIR. To optimize data for future use and replication, datasets must include clear usage licenses, detailed provenance (origin history), and adhere to domain-specific community standards."@en .


###  https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00175
<https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00175> rdf:type owl:NamedIndividual ,
                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00174> ;
                                         <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00201> <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00203> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00204> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00205> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00206> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00207> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00208> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00209> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00210> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00211> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00212> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00213> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00214> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00215> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00216> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00217> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00218> ,
                                                                                  <https://rsna.org/roadmap/ROADMAP_00219> ,
